WEBVTT

00:01.543 --> 00:05.839
♪ (HBO INTRO PLAYS) ♪

00:07.632 --> 00:10.552
One of the things that we
talked about for a while...

00:10.844 --> 00:12.345
"How do you start this show?"

00:12.345 --> 00:15.056
♪ (TENSE MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

00:15.974 --> 00:19.477
CRAIG MAZIN: <i>It was an enormous
undertaking for everyone.</i>

00:20.353 --> 00:23.690
<i>I wouldn't want it to deliver
CG pew-pew</i> (IMITATES EXPLOSION),

00:24.149 --> 00:26.735
but to deliver... reality.

00:26.735 --> 00:28.611
♪ (MUSIC INTENSIFIES) ♪

00:28.611 --> 00:30.989
CREW MEMBER:
Two, one, action!

00:32.782 --> 00:34.367
PEDRO PASCAL:
<i>Negative degree temperatures,</i>

00:34.367 --> 00:36.911
<i>with the wind machine
going like this...</i>

00:36.911 --> 00:37.954
(MIMICS RUDDER SPINNING)

00:38.830 --> 00:41.791
(CHUCKLES) Yeah,
so that was hard. (LAUGHS)

00:41.791 --> 00:44.627
And fun. It was so fun.

00:45.795 --> 00:47.630
The amount of detail
is incredible.

00:47.630 --> 00:50.759
The color schemes, the textures,
how things would flourish.

00:50.759 --> 00:51.676
(INFECTED SCREECHES)

00:51.676 --> 00:52.719
There's everything on this show.

00:53.052 --> 00:57.140
<i>From big scopes of airplanes
to smaller tendrils.</i>

00:59.309 --> 01:02.645
NICO PARKER: <i>You're immediately
just so immersed in</i>

01:02.645 --> 01:04.189
<i>The Last of Us</i> world.

01:05.273 --> 01:08.860
JASON NOLAN: <i>Shooting in Canada,
we're not doing anything small.</i>

01:08.860 --> 01:10.320
It was quite the endeavor.

01:10.320 --> 01:12.572
♪ (MUSIC ESCALATES) ♪

01:13.865 --> 01:15.492
(BLOATER GROWLS)

01:20.371 --> 01:23.917
♪ ("THE LAST OF US" MAIN THEME
BY GUSTAVO SANTAOLALLA PLAYS) ♪

01:23.917 --> 01:26.336
ASHLEY JOHNSON: <i>I remember
when the game came out,</i>

01:26.336 --> 01:28.296
<i>there were so many people saying,</i>

01:28.296 --> 01:30.173
"This needs to be made into
a live action."

01:30.173 --> 01:32.842
I was in conflict with it
at first because I was like,
"We've already done it.

01:32.842 --> 01:35.303
<i>We've shot it,
we've performed it,
we've edited it.</i>

01:35.303 --> 01:37.347
<i>Why do we need to go in
and do this again?"</i>

01:37.347 --> 01:39.474
<i>Neil said,
"At the end of the day,</i>

01:39.474 --> 01:42.268
<i>there are people out there
that will never pick up
a controller,</i>

01:42.268 --> 01:44.312
<i>and they will never experience
this story.</i>

01:44.687 --> 01:47.565
And I think our story
is special enough
to bring it to them."

01:47.857 --> 01:49.776
MERLE DANDRIDGE:
<i>The HBO series,</i>

01:50.068 --> 01:52.487
<i>uh, I don't remember
when I first heard about it,</i>

01:52.487 --> 01:56.658
but when I did, I was like,
"Mommy want that." (LAUGHS)

01:56.658 --> 01:59.410
'Cause I knew it was gonna
be spectacular,

01:59.410 --> 02:01.496
<i>especially when I heard that
it was a collaboration</i>

02:01.496 --> 02:03.164
<i>and that Neil would also
be involved.</i>

02:04.040 --> 02:06.334
When you're casting
these iconic characters,

02:06.334 --> 02:09.879
<i>these characters are iconic
in a cinematic way already.</i>

02:09.879 --> 02:10.839
<i>So now, it's like,</i>

02:11.172 --> 02:13.758
<i>we need to find someone
that can elevate it</i>

02:13.758 --> 02:16.135
<i>or make it their own
in a really interesting way</i>

02:16.135 --> 02:18.221
<i>so it doesn't feel like
they're just duplicating</i>

02:18.221 --> 02:19.722
<i>this other medium.</i>

02:19.722 --> 02:22.100
I learned very quickly

02:22.100 --> 02:25.728
<i>the massive fanbase
that I was stepping into.</i>

02:25.728 --> 02:26.980
<i>I called my sister</i>

02:26.980 --> 02:29.399
<i>to tell her about
the possibility of the job.</i>

02:29.399 --> 02:31.526
<i>And she was in the car
with my nephews.</i>

02:31.526 --> 02:35.530
<i>I didn't even get the S and T
out from the word "Last"</i>

02:35.530 --> 02:36.698
<i>when I said it.</i>

02:36.698 --> 02:39.284
"There's this job,
it's based on a video game.

02:39.284 --> 02:40.368
It's called <i>The La--"</i>

02:40.368 --> 02:42.537
And they were like,
<i>"The Last of Us?!"</i>

02:42.871 --> 02:45.248
And I was like, okay,
I definitely have to do this.

02:45.248 --> 02:47.333
BELLA RAMSEY: <i>I was actually
advised not to play the game,</i>

02:47.333 --> 02:49.085
<i>so that I wouldn't try
and like copy</i>

02:49.085 --> 02:51.462
<i>Ashley Johnson's version
of Ellie, which is incredible.</i>

02:51.462 --> 02:53.673
But I just watched
some of the gameplay though,

02:53.965 --> 02:55.049
secretly, on my own.

02:55.049 --> 02:58.052
JOHNSON: <i>When I met Bella
for the first time,</i>

02:58.052 --> 03:00.138
I was so excited because, obviously,

03:00.138 --> 03:02.348
I'd seen her in <i>Game of Thrones.</i>

03:02.599 --> 03:04.601
<i>And seeing her in person</i>

03:04.601 --> 03:07.186
<i>and even just seeing her on set
and doing scenes,</i>

03:07.186 --> 03:10.106
<i>she has the essence
of Ellie already in her.</i>

03:10.106 --> 03:15.028
Seven, eight, fuck... you.

03:15.320 --> 03:17.572
PASCAL: <i>What's incredible
about what they've done</i>

03:17.572 --> 03:19.240
<i>with these scripts,</i>

03:19.240 --> 03:24.120
<i>was to be able to explore
and nourish things that I think</i>

03:24.370 --> 03:27.081
<i>are very much a part
of the experience of the game.</i>

03:27.081 --> 03:28.124
One of those things

03:28.124 --> 03:31.044
is the internal life
of these characters.

03:31.044 --> 03:33.504
<i>And to really get into the flesh</i>

03:33.504 --> 03:35.590
<i>of what's happening
inside of them.</i>

03:35.590 --> 03:37.091
You want to know what
the biggest surprise

03:37.091 --> 03:38.885
of adapting <i>The Last of Us</i> is?

03:38.885 --> 03:40.470
<i>It's the Neil Druckmann,</i>

03:40.470 --> 03:43.348
<i>the genius who made the game
in the first place,</i>

03:43.348 --> 03:45.391
<i>who created this story,
these characters,</i>

03:45.391 --> 03:46.517
<i>the whole world,</i>

03:46.517 --> 03:50.521
<i>he was so generous
and flexible and smart</i>

03:50.855 --> 03:54.067
about how to re-present
<i>The Last of Us</i>

03:54.067 --> 03:56.569
in a different format
to a whole new audience.

03:57.904 --> 04:01.115
♪ (TENSE MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

04:01.115 --> 04:03.660
(SPEAKING INDONESIAN)

04:03.660 --> 04:06.829
The scientific vision
that the show presents to people

04:06.829 --> 04:08.665
<i>is based absolutely in reality.</i>

04:08.665 --> 04:12.043
<i>That fungus is real,
it does those things to insects,</i>

04:12.043 --> 04:14.712
and if it were to be able
to infect humans,

04:14.712 --> 04:16.255
it would go like that.

04:16.255 --> 04:17.257
It's terrifying.

04:17.590 --> 04:20.802
<i>We want people to feel
the reality of the science here.</i>

04:20.802 --> 04:22.929
(INFECTED PANTING)

04:22.929 --> 04:24.764
Cordyceps, it's a fungus.

04:24.764 --> 04:27.016
<i>And what that fungus does</i>

04:27.016 --> 04:30.520
is it attaches to the brain stem
of an ant,

04:30.520 --> 04:33.106
<i>takes motor control
of the ant's body,</i>

04:33.106 --> 04:35.858
and then attacks the rest
of the ant colony,

04:35.858 --> 04:38.987
spreading the disease
and devouring the other ants.

04:38.987 --> 04:41.531
♪ (UNNERVING MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

04:42.281 --> 04:43.533
MAZIN:
<i>Fungus is a funny word,</i>

04:43.533 --> 04:46.661
<i>but there's so much more of it
than we realize.</i>

04:46.661 --> 04:49.247
Pretty much anywhere
you see grass,

04:49.539 --> 04:51.124
there's fungus
right underneath it.

04:51.124 --> 04:54.585
(INFECTED SCREAMING)

04:55.586 --> 04:56.838
They're connected.

04:57.755 --> 04:58.923
More than you know.

04:58.923 --> 05:00.675
MAZIN: <i>One of the changes
that Neil and I felt</i>

05:00.675 --> 05:01.884
<i>we needed to make early on</i>

05:01.884 --> 05:04.303
<i>was the way the fungus
would spread.</i>

05:04.303 --> 05:05.805
We loved the idea of biting.

05:05.805 --> 05:10.268
We thought that
that was primal and violent.

05:11.477 --> 05:13.896
<i>But we started looking at
something called mycelium,</i>

05:13.896 --> 05:17.358
<i>which are these threads
that make up fungus.</i>

05:17.358 --> 05:18.735
And those threads,

05:18.735 --> 05:21.279
if they get into an insect,
for instance,

05:21.279 --> 05:23.406
that's what starts
to worm its way

05:23.406 --> 05:24.866
towards the insect's brain.

05:28.161 --> 05:31.039
<i>Barrie Gower and his team
did this beautiful work</i>

05:31.039 --> 05:34.125
<i>to mesh humans
and fungus together.</i>

05:35.752 --> 05:38.796
BARRIE GOWER: <i>Initially,
we'd created various
practical tendrils,</i>

05:38.796 --> 05:40.631
which was basically
like a dental plate

05:40.631 --> 05:43.009
that we had inside
the infected character's mouth,

05:43.009 --> 05:46.429
<i>which had all these little
silicon cords joined to.</i>

05:46.429 --> 05:47.680
<i>As soon as you pulled away,</i>

05:47.680 --> 05:49.057
everything started to...
(MIMICS TENDRILS PULLING)

05:49.057 --> 05:50.725
<i>Practically, it looked great.</i>

05:50.725 --> 05:51.976
<i>I think the reality of it</i>

05:51.976 --> 05:55.354
<i>was going to be
the resettability on the day.</i>

05:57.899 --> 06:00.359
<i>Having huge, big fungal pieces
all over the head,</i>

06:00.359 --> 06:01.694
<i>as soon as you took
the eyebrows away,</i>

06:01.694 --> 06:04.280
<i>you started veering into
zombie territory.</i>

06:05.323 --> 06:06.699
NEIL DRUCKMANN: <i>When it has
more of a human side,</i>

06:06.699 --> 06:09.243
<i>more of a beautiful side,
it makes it even scarier.</i>

06:09.243 --> 06:11.245
As a person,
you can relate to it more.

06:11.245 --> 06:12.872
PAUL SPATERI:
<i>From an infected point of view,</i>

06:12.872 --> 06:14.832
<i>we had the first-stage infected.</i>

06:15.333 --> 06:17.460
<i>Very shortly after
they've been bitten,</i>

06:17.460 --> 06:18.461
there's a lot of redness,

06:18.461 --> 06:20.213
a lot of tenderness
around the skin.

06:20.963 --> 06:24.926
<i>Stage two, tiny little things
start breaking through the skin.</i>

06:24.926 --> 06:27.220
<i>They're a bit like the cordyceps
you actually see on ants</i>

06:27.220 --> 06:29.430
or spiders when they've
taken over by the fungus.

06:30.139 --> 06:31.974
<i>Stage three is a slightly bigger
version of that</i>

06:31.974 --> 06:34.519
<i>where you've got real mushrooms
that you can begin to see.</i>

06:34.519 --> 06:35.812
<i>Until you get to stage five,</i>

06:35.812 --> 06:38.106
<i>where the head shape
is distorting.</i>

06:38.481 --> 06:40.942
GOWER: <i>Just basically
breaks through the cranium</i>

06:40.942 --> 06:43.319
<i>and just splits the skull
down the front,</i>

06:43.319 --> 06:45.113
<i>and you have these huge
sort of blooms,</i>

06:45.113 --> 06:46.531
<i>these sort of petals.</i>

06:46.823 --> 06:48.074
No, I didn't want
to look at them.

06:48.074 --> 06:50.284
I didn't want that in my head
to go home and sleep,

06:50.284 --> 06:51.869
<i>and then you have to be
kind of,</i>

06:52.203 --> 06:55.748
you're like, "Hi! How are you?"
(GROANS)

06:57.208 --> 06:58.960
<i>And it's not just kind of
what they look like,</i>

06:58.960 --> 07:01.671
<i>it's the physicality
and the way that they move</i>

07:01.671 --> 07:04.841
<i>is what makes them so creepy.
But impressive.</i>

07:04.841 --> 07:07.135
<i>Not just the prosthetic, obviously,</i>

07:07.135 --> 07:09.846
<i>but the inhabiting of it.</i>

07:09.846 --> 07:13.099
DRUCKMANN:

07:17.937 --> 07:19.647
(GROWLS)

07:19.647 --> 07:20.773
ALEX WANG:
<i>Coming from visual effects,</i>

07:21.065 --> 07:23.151
<i>I think the clicker performances
can be quite challenging</i>

07:23.151 --> 07:25.528
<i>just 'cause
they're very specific.</i>

07:25.528 --> 07:29.323
DRUCKMANN:

07:29.323 --> 07:32.451
He just had this really
amazing performance

07:32.451 --> 07:34.871
and movement study to him.

07:36.080 --> 07:37.540
<i>Those are the type of things</i>

07:37.540 --> 07:41.460
<i>that is quite difficult
to reproduce digitally.</i>

07:41.460 --> 07:44.213
(INFECTED GASPS)

07:45.631 --> 07:48.259
GOWER: <i>These are a lot of our
very early concept and busts.</i>

07:48.259 --> 07:51.554
<i>We're following real reference
and real nature</i>

07:51.554 --> 07:53.472
<i>of real fungus
and real mushrooms.</i>

07:53.931 --> 07:56.267
And just down to the shapes
of the petals.

07:56.267 --> 07:59.061
<i>Underneath,
you've got all these slits
which are called "gills,"</i>

07:59.353 --> 08:01.606
<i>and we always had to make sure
that the orientation</i>

08:01.606 --> 08:04.859
<i>was as such that all the gills
were facing downwards.</i>

08:04.859 --> 08:05.776
<i>And occasionally,</i>

08:06.277 --> 08:07.403
<i>you'd have a piece which
looked really, really great,</i>

08:07.403 --> 08:08.821
<i>but the mushroom's
around the wrong way,</i>

08:08.821 --> 08:09.989
so it's just like... (WHISTLES)

08:09.989 --> 08:11.199
Just move that over
a little bit.

08:11.199 --> 08:13.826
(INFECTED CLICKING)

08:14.952 --> 08:16.245
The sound of the clickers,

08:16.245 --> 08:19.582
we worked so hard to make sure
they sounded just like the game.

08:19.582 --> 08:21.334
MAZIN: Why don't we try some

08:21.334 --> 08:23.419
good, old-fashioned
clicking in the dark?

08:23.419 --> 08:24.295
PHILLIP KOVATS: Yeah.

08:25.213 --> 08:27.256
- Let me just practice a few
so we can make sure--
- AUDIO ENGINEER: Yeah, sure.

08:27.256 --> 08:33.346
(CLICKS)

08:33.638 --> 08:36.140
KOVATS: <i>Misty was the originator
of the sound itself,</i>

08:36.140 --> 08:38.517
and she did these amazing
like throat sounds,

08:38.517 --> 08:39.560
which were like, "That's it!"

08:40.436 --> 08:43.105
<i>And they were like,
"Now we gotta find somebody
who can do it too, like a guy."</i>

08:43.105 --> 08:46.067
- SPEAKER: <i>Right.</i>
- KOVATS: <i>And then I was like,
"I figured it out."</i>

08:46.067 --> 08:48.694
Mr. and Mrs. Clicker.
The original.

08:48.694 --> 08:50.363
The Adam and Eve of clicking.

08:51.030 --> 08:53.991
- (VOCAL RUN) Yeah.
- It's also here, like...

08:53.991 --> 08:55.243
(CLICKING)

08:55.243 --> 08:56.911
MAZIN: I think it's that first
little bit, right?

08:56.911 --> 08:58.412
It's just the initial...
(MIMICS CLICKER)

08:58.412 --> 09:02.250
Which I think isn't bad here,
I just want the real thing.

09:02.250 --> 09:03.918
- Sure.
- Let's do some clicking.

09:03.918 --> 09:10.007
(CLICKING)

09:10.299 --> 09:12.301
- That was good stuff.
I like that.
- MISTY LEE: Thank you.

09:12.301 --> 09:14.095
MAZIN: <i>I love sound,
but it's like--</i>

09:14.095 --> 09:16.138
<i>I don't actually think
I've ever had anything like this</i>

09:16.138 --> 09:18.140
<i>where there was somebody
who knew</i>

09:18.140 --> 09:19.517
<i>how to do this
incredibly specific thing,</i>

09:19.517 --> 09:21.811
<i>and I have the incredibly
specific thing people</i>

09:21.811 --> 09:23.854
<i>doing the incredi--
Oh, this is so cool.</i>

09:24.230 --> 09:25.523
All right, I think
it might be time

09:25.523 --> 09:28.025
to go to the bullpen
and bring in the ol' lefty.

09:28.025 --> 09:33.447
(CLICKING)

09:33.447 --> 09:34.407
Oh, that was a good one.

09:34.407 --> 09:36.033
MISTY: Yeah,
that was a good one!

09:36.033 --> 09:38.119
- I was back here going, "Oh!"
- That felt juicy.

