<i>has such a different way
of working.</i>

15:13.329 --> 15:15.122
<i>The way I worked with Gustavo,</i>

15:15.122 --> 15:16.040
starting with the game

15:16.040 --> 15:17.458
and now continuing
with the show,

15:17.458 --> 15:19.126
is pitch him the story.

15:19.418 --> 15:21.837
<i>I think Gustavo as well
is very much about minimalism.</i>

15:21.837 --> 15:24.173
Like what's the least
we need to do

15:24.173 --> 15:25.090
to achieve this moment?

15:25.591 --> 15:28.427
<i>Which is very much mine
and Craig's philosophy as well.</i>

15:28.677 --> 15:32.514
The whole thing in the music
of <i>The Last of Us</i> from what I do

15:32.514 --> 15:36.560
is to preserve
this organic element.

15:36.560 --> 15:39.980
Kind of minimalism
because I have to play less.

15:40.230 --> 15:44.943
<i>The pipes, the cans, all that
has a little bit to do with</i>

15:44.943 --> 15:49.907
<i>the reality of
a post-disaster world</i>

15:49.907 --> 15:52.826
<i>of found objects, broken things.</i>

15:52.826 --> 15:54.078
<i>But it's very organic.</i>

15:54.078 --> 15:57.331
<i>It's almost like
in primitive folk instrument.</i>

15:57.331 --> 15:59.291
<i>Like a modern primitive folk.</i>

16:02.378 --> 16:04.421
<i>The beginning, you know,
was trying to find</i>

16:04.421 --> 16:08.884
<i>how do we translate the language
from the game to the series,</i>

16:08.884 --> 16:13.263
<i>but I think we have found now
something that kind of flows.</i>

16:15.015 --> 16:16.016
DRUCKMANN:
<i>He would go off,</i>

16:16.350 --> 16:19.561
<i>and he's come back with
an hour or more of music.</i>

16:19.561 --> 16:21.105
<i>And we'd just
sit here listening.</i>

