17:04.314 --> 17:07.192
SEAN NOWLAN: <i>Visual effects
is a big part of this show.</i>

17:08.944 --> 17:10.446
Every shot that we shoot

17:10.696 --> 17:13.198
needs to be touched in some way
by visual effects.

17:14.366 --> 17:18.495
There's such an effort
to really push the boundaries

17:18.495 --> 17:22.416
on both what is practical
and what is a visual effect.

17:22.833 --> 17:24.126
Right from the get-go,

17:24.126 --> 17:28.672
the impetus was to try and do
as much practical as possible.

17:29.381 --> 17:32.092
<i>Alex understands
that the dovetail</i>

17:32.092 --> 17:34.386
<i>between practical
and visual effects,</i>

17:34.803 --> 17:38.640
<i>when you make it seamless,
that's the magic.</i>

17:42.936 --> 17:46.106
GOWER:
<i>It is very interesting working
with Alex and the VFX team.</i>

17:46.106 --> 17:48.192
The visual effects department
is probably the one department

17:48.192 --> 17:49.610
we work probably
the closest with

17:49.610 --> 17:51.111
on any given show or film.

17:51.570 --> 17:54.531
<i>They benefit a lot more
from having something there
on the day,</i>

17:54.531 --> 17:57.201
<i>which they can either manipulate
or augment in post</i>

17:57.201 --> 17:59.161
<i>or they've got something there
that needs a touch.</i>

18:00.120 --> 18:01.288
There's everything on this show,

18:01.288 --> 18:03.499
from airplane crashes,

18:05.167 --> 18:07.002
<i>to big environments,</i>

18:07.920 --> 18:11.465
<i>to war-torn destruction
in a big city,</i>

18:12.424 --> 18:14.384
<i>to smaller tendrils.</i>

18:14.384 --> 18:17.221
<i>So, there's a lot
for visual effects to work on.</i>

18:17.596 --> 18:19.264
<i>Because there's
a lot of environments,</i>

18:19.264 --> 18:21.850
<i>we've actually used
a lot of drone scanning,</i>

18:21.850 --> 18:24.603
<i>so that we're able
to recreate it digitally.</i>

18:25.270 --> 18:28.315
BLAINE LOUGHEED: <i>On this show,
we used a combination of drones
and LiDAR.</i>

18:28.315 --> 18:32.486
<i>LiDAR scanning is
light imaging distance ranging.</i>

18:32.486 --> 18:36.657
And it basically
gives you a 3D model
of what you're scanning.

18:36.657 --> 18:39.535
<i>We knew that there would be
a lot of environment work,</i>

18:39.535 --> 18:40.577
<i>in line with the game.</i>

18:41.078 --> 18:44.456
<i>There's a lot of overgrowth,
and everything's deteriorated.</i>

18:44.456 --> 18:47.000
And we knew that
we would have to pretty much

18:47.000 --> 18:49.878
<i>help out in every episode
in that respect.</i>

18:54.925 --> 18:58.178
So, there's a couple
of different types of scanning
that we're doing on the show.

18:58.178 --> 19:00.389
<i>One of them is cyber scanning.</i>

19:00.389 --> 19:02.975
<i>It's a circle of cameras
and lights</i>

19:02.975 --> 19:04.810
<i>that flash simultaneously.</i>

19:05.144 --> 19:06.979
We scan every character
that's on a show,

19:06.979 --> 19:09.857
<i>in case we need to build
a digital version of them.</i>

19:10.732 --> 19:12.860
