seven feet tall,</i>

24:27.674 --> 24:30.051
<i>you can get a man and put him
in a prosthetic suit,</i>

24:30.051 --> 24:31.052
<i>which they did.</i>

24:31.052 --> 24:32.179
<i>At the end of the day,</i>

24:32.179 --> 24:33.597
<i>there's only a certain amount
of mobility</i>

24:33.597 --> 24:34.931
<i>in this prosthetic suit.</i>

24:34.931 --> 24:37.475
<i>As good as it looked,
he just couldn't do the things</i>

24:37.475 --> 24:39.895
<i>that he needed to do
as the bloater.</i>

24:40.353 --> 24:43.190
<i>Very early on, we kind of
planned for doing it</i>

24:43.190 --> 24:44.232
practically on set,

24:44.232 --> 24:46.693
in a prosthetic suit
that Barrie Gower made.

24:46.693 --> 24:49.654
<i>But we reserved the option
and shot a lot of clean plates,</i>

24:49.654 --> 24:52.490
<i>which means we took the bloater,
the physical bloater,</i>

24:52.490 --> 24:55.911
<i>out of the shot so that we had
a clean background to use</i>

24:55.911 --> 24:58.330
<i>in case we wanted to go
the CG route</i>

24:58.330 --> 25:00.290
<i>in some or in all cases.</i>

25:00.290 --> 25:02.709
WANG: <i>Barrie Gower
and his team did a fantastic job</i>

25:02.709 --> 25:05.337
<i>creating the bloater suit
with so much detail.</i>

25:05.670 --> 25:08.006
However, we found that
what we needed

25:08.006 --> 25:10.091
was the bloater to be
a little bit bigger.

25:10.091 --> 25:12.469
<i>And it needed to move
a little faster, as well.</i>

25:12.469 --> 25:15.764
NOWLAN:
<i>This CG creature is doing
some very fantastical things.</i>

25:15.764 --> 25:18.099
<i>Things that a normal human
couldn't do.</i>

25:18.099 --> 25:21.770
We ended up just feeling like
it was necessary to create

25:21.770 --> 25:23.271
a full digital version
of the bloater.

25:23.271 --> 25:25.190
(GUNFIRE)

25:25.190 --> 25:29.861
(BLOATER ROARS)

25:31.404 --> 25:33.031
NOWLAN: <i>In the case of
the child clicker,</i>

25:33.031 --> 25:34.699
<i>very much like
the bloater early on,</i>

25:34.699 --> 25:37.744
<i>what we did was we sussed out</i>

25:37.744 --> 25:38.995
<i>a person that could
play the role.</i>

25:38.995 --> 25:40.330
<i>And in this case,
it happened to be</i>

25:40.580 --> 25:44.209
<i>a girl from Toronto called Skye,
who was also a contortionist.</i>

25:44.209 --> 25:47.921
<i>So she could move her body
very, very effectively</i>

25:47.921 --> 25:51.675
<i>and do all sorts of clicker-y,
kind of stutter-y motions.</i>

25:52.926 --> 25:55.971
<i>What we did was we shot Skye
on set, like the bloater.</i>

25:55.971 --> 25:59.599
<i>And then we also decided
to sort of change the design</i>

25:59.599 --> 26:03.353
<i>just ever so slightly, in terms
of the prosthetic makeup.</i>

26:03.353 --> 26:06.231
We wanted to feel frightened
by her character,

26:06.231 --> 26:08.900
but also have a sense
of sympathy for her.

26:09.484 --> 26:12.112
<i>We had more of
her face exposed,</i>

26:12.362 --> 26:15.448
<i>we could see her long hair,
her pigtails.</i>

26:15.448 --> 26:18.451
<i>These were all the aspects
that were important to
Craig and Neil.</i>

26:19.744 --> 26:24.291
NOWLAN: <i>What started out as
just replacing Skye's head
as a CG element,</i>

26:24.291 --> 26:27.711
<i>we realized we might as well
go a full CG body on it.</i>

26:27.711 --> 26:29.921
<i>And then we can get
this child clicker to do</i>

26:29.921 --> 26:31.840
<i>exactly what we want it to do.</i>

26:31.840 --> 26:35.510
<i>So, now she's able to do that
in a much more fantastical way</i>

26:35.510 --> 26:37.345
<i>because we went CG with it.</i>

26:39.973 --> 26:43.184
LOUGHEED: <i>The fight
at the Silver Lake Steakhouse,</i>

26:43.184 --> 26:45.186
special effects did
an excellent job

26:45.186 --> 26:48.398
<i>of essentially piping
the entire set.</i>

26:48.398 --> 26:50.358
<i>Of course, we can see
some of this piping,</i>

26:50.358 --> 26:52.652
<i>which, this is where
visual effects will come in</i>

26:52.652 --> 26:57.574
and remove the piping
and also blend in more flames.

26:58.074 --> 27:01.244
WHIST: <i>At one point, we were not
going to do any practical fire</i>

27:01.244 --> 27:04.205
<i>because the discussion was
that it was too much money,</i>

27:04.581 --> 27:06.291
<i>and we couldn't do it
in the time we had.</i>

27:06.291 --> 27:08.918
<i>That's where I come in to say,
"No, we can do it."</i>

27:08.918 --> 27:10.545
<i>Basically, I said,
"You can have--</i>

27:10.545 --> 27:14.174
Of this size set, you can have
a quarter of it on fire."

27:14.924 --> 27:17.635
NOWLAN: <i>Joel Whist,
our special effects supervisor,</i>

27:18.053 --> 27:19.304
is amazing,

27:19.304 --> 27:21.639
and he designed
that entire set

27:21.639 --> 27:25.060
<i>to be fireproof in the areas
that we needed it to be.</i>

27:25.060 --> 27:27.645
<i>And that helped immeasurably
for us.</i>

27:29.439 --> 27:34.361
♪ ("THE LAST OF US (YOU AND ME)"
BY GUSTAVO SANTAOLALLA PLAYS) ♪

27:35.111 --> 27:37.238
PALMER: <i>Shooting with
Nabo the giraffe</i>

27:37.238 --> 27:40.450
will certainly be
one of my favorite experiences.

27:40.825 --> 27:44.496
<i>What I quickly learned after
doing the research on the game</i>

27:44.496 --> 27:47.248
<i>was just how
critically important</i>

27:47.248 --> 27:50.960
<i>this one moment is
to the whole story of the game.</i>

27:51.669 --> 27:53.463
Giraffes are pretty massive.

27:54.756 --> 27:58.051
It's like a spiritual experience almost,

27:58.301 --> 28:02.013
<i>being so close
to such a magnificent animal.</i>

28:02.514 --> 28:04.974
Yes, you can create a giraffe
in visual effects,

28:04.974 --> 28:06.434
but it's just not the same.

28:07.769 --> 28:11.398
Fortunately,
the one thing Alberta does have
is a zoo with giraffes.

28:11.398 --> 28:15.944
And we spent quite a while
putting things in the enclosure,

28:15.944 --> 28:19.072
<i>so that we could shoot it
and getting the giraffes acclimated.</i>

28:19.072 --> 28:21.574
<i>Like panels with blue screen,</i>

28:21.825 --> 28:25.078
<i>so that we could go in there
and just shoot the giraffe</i>

28:25.078 --> 28:26.830
<i>and have Ellie feed the giraffe.</i>

28:27.205 --> 28:30.959
PALMER:
<i>And then, visual effects in
all the other pieces around it.</i>

28:32.877 --> 28:33.878
Something that was
so fascinating

28:33.878 --> 28:35.380
about this experience was that

28:35.380 --> 28:37.632
<i>the visual effects
and the special effects</i>

28:37.632 --> 28:39.300
<i>and all of the departments
working together,</i>

28:39.300 --> 28:41.302
<i>building all of these
practical elements.</i>

28:41.302 --> 28:45.723
<i>To be able to actually see it
in front of you was everything</i>

28:46.015 --> 28:48.143
<i>in terms of the playing
of these characters</i>

28:48.143 --> 28:51.229
<i>and the being in
this fungus apocalypse</i>

28:51.646 --> 28:52.772
<i>20 years in.</i>

28:57.527 --> 29:00.864
♪ ("THE PATH (A NEW BEGINNING)"
BY GUSTAVO SANTAOLALLA PLAYS) ♪

29:01.948 --> 29:04.534
DRUCKMANN:
<i>I don't know how to describe
this feeling of pride.</i>

29:04.534 --> 29:06.619
<i>And I can't wait for everybody
at Naughty Dog</i>

29:06.619 --> 29:08.163
<i>that worked so hard on the game</i>

29:08.163 --> 29:11.291
<i>and realize that the first time
to see this version</i>

29:11.291 --> 29:12.792
does all their work justice.

29:13.084 --> 29:15.670
<i>There's something really
beautiful and moving about that.</i>

29:16.838 --> 29:18.923
When people talk to me
about the game,

29:18.923 --> 29:20.008
we are the same.

29:20.008 --> 29:21.926
We understand each other.

29:21.926 --> 29:23.845
<i>We have a shared language.</i>

29:24.554 --> 29:25.472
<i>Arts are so important</i>

29:25.805 --> 29:27.640
<i>because it holds a mirror
to our social condition,</i>

29:28.016 --> 29:30.643
<i>and it helps us
have better understanding</i>

29:30.643 --> 29:33.688
<i>for someone who doesn't look
or act like us,</i>

29:33.688 --> 29:35.440
<i>who might come from
a different culture,</i>

29:35.440 --> 29:38.943
<i>and I think that we'll be able
to jump over some of these</i>

29:38.943 --> 29:40.904
<i>skyscraper-high hurdles</i>

29:40.904 --> 29:43.573
that we have in the things
that divide us.

29:43.990 --> 29:46.826
<i>And that will never end.</i>

29:46.826 --> 29:50.872
That right there is the crux
of <i>The Last of Us.</i>

29:51.998 --> 29:54.918
PASCAL: <i>One of the most
exciting experiences of my life</i>

29:54.918 --> 29:57.128
<i>was getting this job.</i>

29:57.128 --> 30:01.549
To come back to HBO,
which basically raised me,

30:01.549 --> 30:06.221
<i>to meet Craig, to meet Bella,
all of our different actors,</i>

30:06.221 --> 30:09.474
<i>there was something of where
I knew this was going to be</i>

30:09.474 --> 30:14.562
the hardest and the best
experience of my life.

30:14.562 --> 30:16.147
<i>And weirdly,
there was something</i>

30:16.147 --> 30:19.817
<i>that I knew was special
and terrifying.</i>

30:19.817 --> 30:22.111
And it all came true.
(LAUGHS)

30:23.905 --> 30:28.368
On the first day,
I set a fairly reasonable goal

30:28.368 --> 30:30.828
to make the best
television show ever.

30:30.828 --> 30:32.413
That was our reasonable goal.

30:33.164 --> 30:37.502
I just want to say thank you.
I love you guys. Thank you.

30:37.835 --> 30:40.296
(CHEERING, CLAPPING)

30:40.547 --> 30:45.134
♪ ("THE LAST OF US" MAIN THEME
CONTINUES) ♪

31:05.572 --> 31:07.490
And that's the end
of this story.
